<h2>Introduction
</h2>
<p>Teamwork is a necessary part of a successful career. Employers want to hire people who know the value and power of working as a cohesive team - especially those who understand that not everyone can be a leader all the time. As we saw during our in-class activity, the puzzle became easier to solve when the groups worked together as cohesive units.
</p>
<p class="txtbk-pullquote">â€œTeam: A collection of individuals who are interdependent in their tasks and who share responsibility for the outcomes. Teams enable people to cooperate, enhance individual skills and provide constructive feedback without any conflict between individuals."
</p>
<p>There are certain qualities that successful teams tend to have. These qualities will be important to keep in mind as we begin our group projects.
</p>
<p><strong>7 C's to Successful Teams</strong>
</p>
<ol><li>Clear Communication: share opinions, perspectives, and alternatives; listen; have a plan and clarify responsibilities</li><li>Collaboration/Coordination/Cooperation: review progress; encourage cooperation, not competition; trust</li><li>Compromise</li><li>Commitment: set clear goals and work towards them; share the work <u>and</u> do the work</li><li>Competence/Contribution: each member has the knowledge, skills, behaviors, and attitudes to perform their roles</li><li>Culture: create a culture of trust and respect; focus on the positive aspects of each team member; be enthusiastic</li><li>Creativity: reward out-of-the box thinking; dedicate time to team building; encourage brainstorming</li><li>(Bonus "C") Celebration: reward hard work&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
